or urban design that one understands their form and structure, their functional conditions, and the differentiation into private and public spheres, as well as the ways they are networked into their surroundings. Study of these city building blocks represents a first step toward understanding, and successfully developing the built structure of the city as a physical and social habitat.Themes are - the row, - the block, - the courtyard (the block in reverse), - the passageway, - the line, - the solitaire, - the group, - the "shed".  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aBasics. 4aErschließung. 4aGebäudeform. 4aLehrbuch Architektur. 4aStadtbauelement. 4aStadtplanung. 4aStadtstruktur. 4aStudienliteratur Architektur. 4aStädtebau. 4aUrbanismus. 7aARCHITECTURE / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh1 aPeterek, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBASICS ONLINE PAKET DEUTSCHz9783035611649oZDB-23-BON08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2019z97831107195670 cEPUBz97830356126220 cprintz978303561002440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978303561307040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783035613070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783035613070/original  a978-3-11-069627-1  DG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1b2020  a978-3-11-071956-7  DG Plus eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-BON